  "response": "## The bug\n\n`crime_00010` (Timezone Roulette, `src/date.ts:29,33`) flags two `new Date(\"…\")` calls parsing strings with no timezone marker. The literal responsible for the \"day early in Europe\" symptom is:\n\n**`\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\"` at line 29.**\n\nWhy this one and not the date-only `\"2026-12-20\"` on line 33: per the ECMAScript spec, an ISO datetime *without* an offset is parsed as **local time**, whereas a date-only form (`YYYY-MM-DD`) is parsed as **UTC**. So:\n\n- CI (UTC server): `new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")` → `2026-12-25T07:00:00Z`.\n- European browser (CET/CEST): same literal → `2026-12-25T06:00:00Z` (or earlier under CEST). Combined with whatever `today`/midnight comparison the promo gate does — and given crime_00004 flagging mixed UTC + local method reads on the same receiver — that 1–2 hour drift is enough to land on the previous calendar day, so the gate opens a day early.\n\n## Smallest change\n\nAppend `Z` to the literal so it parses as UTC everywhere, matching the CI server:\n\n```ts\n// src/date.ts:29\n- new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00\")\n+ new Date(\"2026-12-25T07:00:00Z\")\n```\n\nThat's the minimal diff: no function rename, no library, no new clock injection. It makes production parsing match CI parsing for the promo start instant. The line-33 `\"2026-12-20\"` already parses as UTC, so it isn't the cause of *this* bug — leave it for a separate cleanup (or normalise it to `\"2026-12-20T00:00:00Z\"` for explicitness) rather than bundling it into the bugfix.",
